{
  "text": "When NO is generated, it is easily oxidized to nitrite and stored in intracellular and extracellular fluids [CITATION_1] . Thus, in experiments, the levels of nitrite (a stable product of NO) are usually measured to reflect the amount of NO [CITATION_2] . In macrophages, macrophage-inducible NO synthase is mainly responsible for NO production in response to various stimuli [CITATION_3] . NO then acts as an intercellular messenger and is a versatile player in the immune system. In our study, all the concentrations tested induce NO to various extents in a dose-dependent manner (Figure 4a ). S8 and S6 induced similar levels (the highest levels) of NO in the culture supernatant. Even lower concentrations (100 μg/ml) of S6 and S8 induced NO production and this agrees with an earlier study which reported that 100 μg/ml of a plant extract strongly induced macNOS mRNA expression [CITATION_4] . The ability of the extracts to induce NO secretion by RAW 264.7 cells may reflect the potential to modulate NO-based strategies for pathogen-mediated immune response for treating infections and tumors.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "29005280",
